title: A Phase II, Multicenter, Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled, Parallel-Group, Efficacy, and Safety Study of MTAU9937A in Patients With Moderate Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This Phase II, multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, parallel-group study will evaluate the clinical efficacy, safety, pharmacokinetics, and pharmacodynamics of semorinemab in patients with moderate AD. The study consists of a screening period, a double-blind treatment period, an optional open-label extension (OLE) period, and a safety follow-up period. There may be up to two study cohorts.

milestones.comment: Participants who completed the double-blind treatment period (before implementation of Protocol Version 3), or participants who completed the double-blind study drug treatment through Week 45 without any missed doses of study drug (after implementation of Protocol Version 4), were assigned to Cohort 1. In Cohort 1, the double-blind treatment period has a duration of 48 weeks.

Participants who were active in the double-blind treatment period (after implementation of Protocol Version 3) or participants who missed one or more study drug dose (after implementation of Protocol version 4) were assigned to Cohort 2. In Cohort 2, the double-blind treatment period has a duration of 60 weeks.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to Last Visit of Double-Blind Treatment Period on the Clinical Dementia Rating-Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB)
outcomeMeasures.description: The Clinical Dementia Rating-Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) is a scale used to quantify the severity of symptoms of dementia. The CDR-SB is obtained through interviews of patients and informants, and disease severity is rated in 6 domains of functioning: memory, orientation, judgment and problem solving, community affairs, home and hobbies, and personal care. Each domain is rated on a 5-point scale of functioning as follows: 0, no impairment; 0.5, questionable impairment; 1, mild impairment; 2, moderate impairment; and 3, severe impairment (personal care is scored on a 4-point scale without a 0.5 rating available). The CDR-SB score is obtained by summing each of the domain box scores, with scores ranging from 0 to 18, with the higher values representing more severe impairment.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: The modified intent-to-treat population included all randomized participants who received at least one dose of study drug and had at least one baseline and one postbaseline ADAS-Cog11 and the CDR-SB score at the given time point.
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Baseline to Week 49 for Cohorts 1 and 2, and Baseline to Week 61 for Cohort 2

outcomeMeasures.title: Percentage of Participants With Adverse Events
outcomeMeasures.description: An Adverse Event is any untoward medical occurrence in a subject administered a pharmaceutical product and which does not necessarily have to have a causal relationship with the treatment. An adverse event can therefore be any unfavorable and unintended sign (including an abnormal laboratory finding, for example), symptom, or disease temporally associated with the use of a pharmaceutical product, whether or not considered related to the pharmaceutical product. Preexisting conditions which worsen during a study are also considered as adverse events.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: The safety population included all randomized participants who received at least one dose of either semorinemab or placebo.
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Baseline up to end of study (approximately 4 years and 7 months)

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product semorinemab (also listed as MTAU9937A / RO7105705) is a humanized monoclonal antibody that targets tau protein — i.e., a biologic aimed at an Alzheimer’s disease pathology (tau). This indicates a disease-targeted biologic approach rather than a symptomatic/cognitive-only therapy. citeturn0search2turn0search1

Act (key extracted details): Trial NCT03828747/MTAU9937A is a Phase II, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled study of semorinemab in moderate AD. Semorinemab is described in preclinical and early clinical reports as an anti-tau IgG4 monoclonal antibody that binds all six human tau isoforms and shows target engagement. The trial entry lists semorinemab (MTAU9937A/RO7105705) as the active drug and placebo as control. citeturn0search1turn0search2turn0search8

Reflect: Classification check — because semorinemab is an antibody directed at tau pathology (intended to modify disease-related pathology/spread), it fits the definition of a "disease-targeted biologic." Note: Phase II results have been mixed (some signals in certain endpoints/cohorts reported and other trials failed to meet primary endpoints), and clinical development status has evolved; these outcome details do not change the mechanism-of-action classification but are relevant context. citeturn0search7turn0search5turn0search12
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational product semorinemab (MTAU9937A / RO7105705; semorinemab) is a humanized IgG4 monoclonal antibody that binds the N‑terminal domain of tau and was developed to bind full‑length, phosphorylated and oligomeric tau species and to slow cell‑to‑cell spread of tau pathology — i.e., the intervention directly targets tau pathology rather than symptomatic neurotransmitter systems. citeturn0search8turn0search7

Act: Key extracted details from the trial description and literature: the Phase II Lauriet study (NCT03828747) tested semorinemab in mild‑to‑moderate AD (MTAU9937A listed as the investigational drug); semorinemab is described as an anti‑tau monoclonal antibody that binds all six human tau isoforms (N‑terminal epitope, residues ~6–23) and shows target engagement in humans and preclinical models. These facts identify the biological focus as tau-directed immunotherapy. citeturn0search4turn0search8turn0search6

Reflect: Semorinemab’s mechanism (anti‑tau passive immunotherapy) maps directly to CADRO category B) Tau. The intervention is a disease‑targeted biologic aimed at modulating tau pathology rather than a symptomatic, multi‑target, or non‑therapeutic procedure, so the most specific CADRO assignment is B) Tau. (Noted that clinical outcomes have been mixed/negative on some endpoints, but this does not change the mechanism‑of‑action classification.) citeturn0search8turn0search2
